I think the big requirements from when I built this for phosphor-webui were:
1. It can handle webui route fragments (ex /#sensors).
2. It can handle non-webui routes (ex /redfish/v1)
3. It explicitly rejects URLs that include a domain (ex <mybmc>/login?next="https://www.google.com" should forward to the homepage, or error), not forward to google.

It looks like the patchset currently does #1 only.

I didn't mean to be opaque in my earlier comment about security.  I was lacking in time to type a more complete response.

Patch Set 1:

> LGTM.
> 
> Zev had queries about this on the mailing list so I'll give it a bit longer to have a chance to respond.

Andrew's reply on the list explained that the defconfigs are intended to cover a fairly broad range of hardware, and that OpenBMC builds should override that with a more platform-specific config of their own, though at the moment I'm having trouble finding good examples of that -- pretty much all the kernel configs I see in the OpenBMC tree just seem to be adding various `=y` settings, so effectively just creating larger supersets of the defconfig if I'm understanding things right (I will say I'm not super clear on the difference between the defconfigs in the kernel tree and the ones in the meta-aspeed layer though).

While offhand I don't recall having seen any problems with the kernel itself, it does seem in general like we've been dealing with some issues with code size as of late (CI failures due to image fitment problems; default u-boot builds not fitting in the space allotted to them in the default partition layout), so I'm just a bit hesitant to enable features that (I think) are likely to end up as dead weight on all but a few systems unless each platform goes out of its way to turn them back off.  I don't know how much precedent this would hypothetically overturn, or how much hard-learned community wisdom I might be blithely ignorant of here, but I think I'd be inclined more toward a general model of the defconfig providing a somewhat lean baseline and platforms enabling the additional features they need on top of that (which seems slightly more in line with what appears to happen in practice, given the near-empty output from `git grep '=n' '*/linux-aspeed/*.cfg'`).

All that said, it's not a strenuous objection (not -1-ing this), just tossing out some thoughts for whatever they happen to be worth -- so if the general consensus is in favor I'm fine if this change goes in.

Please take a look at https://github.com/openbmc/docs/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md#inclusive-naming. We as a project have tried to deprecate certain terms (i.e. whitelist == allowlist).

One issue we have with our AST2600 and eMMC usage is that we preserve /etc and /var across firmware updates. There are times where we'd like to do a mini factory reset, where we keep the network settings and maybe a few other things, but clear most everything else. I wonder if this design is something we could build on for that type of function. This is mostly a "clean-up-the-lab-system" type function.

For AST2600, /etc and /var are only preserved when flashing the normal `mtd.tar` images but not the `mtd.all.tar` images, in which case preservation is handled on a per-file basis by the update script. This design is to allow managing the configuration of this update script, which may be more desirable than preserving the entire rwfs for some use-cases.
